The article discusses the importance of human rights and the Universal Declaration of Human Rights (UDHR) in promoting a safer future for all nations. It emphasizes the need to continue working towards achieving equality and dignity for all. The United States is committed to advancing human rights domestically and internationally, as demonstrated by its intention to rejoin the United Nations Human Rights Council. The article also highlights the importance of leading by example and strengthening democracy at home. The Biden administration is taking steps to address historical challenges and promote racial equity and support for underserved communities. The article concludes by announcing the Summit for Democracy, where global leaders will come together to address threats to democracy and reaffirm their commitment to human rights. The President proclaims December 10, 2021, as Human Rights Day and the week beginning December 10, 2021, as Human Rights Week, calling upon the people of the United States to observe these occasions with appropriate ceremonies and activities.